    "reasoning": "1. The goal is to find the minimum value among four 8-bit unsigned inputs: a, b, c, and d.\n2. To achieve this, I can perform sequential comparisons. First, find the minimum of a and b. Then, find the minimum of that result and c. Finally, find the minimum of that result and d.\n3. Since the specification does not mention a clock or reset, this should be implemented as purely combinational logic using continuous assignments or an `always @(*)` block.\n4. I will use the ternary operator `? :` to implement the comparison-and-selection logic concisely.\n5. Syntax advice: \n   - Ensure all input and output port widths match the specification (8 bits each).\n   - Use `logic` for all signal declarations to maintain SystemVerilog standards.\n   - When using ternary operators, ensure the types of both branches are compatible to avoid unexpected bit-width issues.\n   - Ensure the module name is exactly `TopModule` as requested.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic [7:0] a,\n    input  logic [7:0] b,\n    input  logic [7:0] c,\n    input  logic [7:0] d,\n    output logic [7:0] min\n);\n\n    // Combinational logic to find the minimum of four values\n    // Step 1: min_ab = min(a, b)\n    // Step 2: min_abc = min(min_ab, c)\n    // Step 3: min = min(min_abc, d)\n\n    logic [7:0] min_ab;\n    logic [7:0] min_abc;\n\n    always @(*) begin\n        // Compare a and b\n        if (a < b) begin\n            min_ab = a;\n        end else begin\n            min_ab = b;\n        end\n\n        // Compare min_ab and c\n        if (min_ab < c) begin\n            min_abc = min_ab;\n        end else begin\n            min_abc = c;\n        end\n\n        // Compare min_abc and d\n        if (min_abc < d) begin\n            min = min_abc;\n        end else begin\n            min = d;\n        end\n    end\n\nendmodule"
